ion=Princeton, NJ|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1992|isbn=0-691-00880-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=614pd07OtfQC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Brock|first1=Roger|last2=Hodkinson|first2=Stephen|title=Alternatives to Athens: Varieties of Political Organization|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2000|isbn=0-19-815220-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HS-DAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|last=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Epirus\")|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/190156/Epirus|title=Epirus|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc.|year=2013|accessdate=1 July 2013|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Errington|first=Robert Malcolm|title=A History of Macedonia|location=Berkeley, CA|publisher=University of California Press|year=1990|isbn=0-520-06319-8|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_PYgkqP_s1PQC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Philip of Macedon|location=London|publisher=Duckworth|year=1998|isbn=0-7156-2829-1| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0XF5OwAACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|chapter=CHAPTER 9d. ILLYRIANS AND NORTH-WEST GREEKS|pages=422\u2013443|editor-last1=Lewis|editor-first1=David Malcolm|editor-last2=Boardman|editor-first2=John|editor-last3=Hornblower|editor-first3=Simon|editor-last4=Ostwald|editor-first4=M.|title=The Cambridge Ancient History: The Fourth Century B.C.|volume=VI|edition=2nd|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1994|isbn=0-521-23348-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vx251bK988gC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=A History of Greece to 322 B.C|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1986|isbn=0-19-873096-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KwHBQgAACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|chapter=CHAPTER 40 ILLYRIS, EPIRUS AND MACEDONIA|pages=261\u2013285|editor-last1=Boardman|editor-first1=John|editor-last2=Hammond|editor-first2=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=The Cambridge Ancient History: The Expansion of the Greek World, Eighth to Sixth Centuries B.C.|volume=III, Part 3|edition=2nd |location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1982|isbn=0-521-23447-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qAoqP4g1fEC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hornblower|first=Simon|title=The Greek World, 479\u2013323 BC|location=New York and London|publisher=Routledge|year=2002|isbn=0-415-16326-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wvtyijSRcKUC|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hornblower|first1=Simon|last2=Spawforth|first2=Antony|last3=Eidinow|first3=Esther|title=The Oxford Classical Dictionary|year=2012|edition=4th|origyear=1949|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-954556-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bVWcAQAAQBAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Horsley|first=G. H. R.|title=New Documents Illustrating Early Christianity: A Review of the Greek Inscriptions and Papyri Published in 1979|location=Grand Rapids, MI|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|year=1987|isbn=0-85837-599-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uVPSFtaE5H4C|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Liddell|first1=Henry George|last2=Scott|first2=Robert|title=An Intermediate Greek-English Lexicon|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1889|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0058|ref=harv}} \n*{{cite book|last=Smith|first=William|title=Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology|volume=I|location=London|publisher=Taylor and Walton, Upper Gower Street|year=1844|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0CUBAAAAQAAJ|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wilkes|first=John|title=The Illyrians|location=Oxford|publisher=Blackwell Publishers Limited|year=1995|origyear=1992|isbn=0-631-19807-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Nv6SPRKqs8C|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Woodbury|first=Leonard|title=Neoptolemus at Delphi: Pindar, \"Nem.\" 7.30 ff.|journal=Phoenix|volume=33|number=2|pages=95\u2013133|year=1979|publisher=Classical Association of Canada|jstor=1087989|ref=harv}}\n{{refend|2}}\n\n[[Category:Alexander the Great]]\n[[Category:Ancient tribes in Epirus]]\n[[Category:Greek tribes]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the micronation of Molossia|Republic of Molossia|the dog type|Molosser}}\n[[File:Map of ancient Epirus and environs (English).svg|right|thumb|215px|Tribes of Epirus in antiquity.]]\n\nThe '''Molossians''' ({{Lang-grc|\u039c\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03c3\u03c3\u03bf\u03af|translit=Molossoi}}) were an ancient [[Greeks|Greek]] tribe and kingdom that inhabited [[Epirus|the region of Epirus]] since the [[Helladic period|Mycenaean]] era.<ref>{{harvnb|Borza|1992|pp=62, 78, 98}}; {{harvnb|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica (\"Epirus\")|2013}}; {{harvnb|Errington|1990|p=43}}; {{harvnb|Hammond|1998|p=19}}; {{harvnb|Hammond|1994|pp=430, 433\u2013434}}; {{harvnb|Hammond|1982|p=284}}; {{harvnb|Wilkes|1995|p=104}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hornblower|Spawforth|Eidinow|2012|loc=p. 966: \"'''Molossi''', common name of tribes forming a tribal state (koinon) in Epirus, which originated in northern Pindus including the Orestae, FGrH 1 F 107) and expanded southwards, reaching the Ambraciote Gulf (see AMBRACIA) c.370 BC.\"}}</ref> On their northern frontier, they had the [[Chaonians]] and on their southern frontier the kingdom of the [[Thesprotians]]. The Molossians were part of the [[The Epirote League#Epirote League (231\u2013167 BC)|League of Epirus]] until they sided against Rome in the [[Third Macedonian War]] (171\u2013168 BC).\n\n==Mythology==\nAccording to [[Greek mythology]], the Molossians were the descendants of [[Molossus (son of Neoptolemus)|Molossus]], one of the three sons of [[Neoptolemus]], son of [[Achilles]] and [[Deidamia (mythology)|Deidamia]]. Following the sack of [[Troy]], Neoptolemus and his armies settled in Epirus where they joined with the local population. Molossus inherited the kingdom of Epirus after the death of [[Helenus]], son of [[Priam]] and [[Hecuba]] of Troy, who had married his erstwhile sister-in-law [[Andromache]] after Neoptolemus's death.  According to some historians, their first king was Phaethon, one of those who came into [[Epirus]] with [[Pelasgus]]. According to [[Plutarch]], [[Deucalion]] and [[Pyrrha]], having set up the worship of [[Zeus]] at [[Dodona]], settled there among the Molossians.<ref name=\"Pyrrhus\">Plutarch. ''Parallel Lives'', \"[http://classics.mit.edu/Plutarch/pyrrhus.html Pyrrhus]\".</ref>\n\n==Ancient sources==\n[[File:Molossi, Epirus.jpg|right|thumb|215px|Coin of Molossi, 360\u2013330/25 BC. Obverse: Vertical [[thunderbolt]] on shield, \u039c\u039f\u039b\u039f\u03a3\u03a3\u03a9\u039d (of Molossians) around shield. Reverse: Thunderbolt within wreath.]]\n\nAccording to [[Strabo]], the Molossians, along with the [[Chaonians]] and [[Thesprotians]], were the most famous among the fourteen tribes of Epirus, who once ruled over the whole [[Epirus|region]]. The Chaonians ruled Epirus at an earlier time, and afterwards the Thesprotians and Molossians controlled the region. The Thesprotians, the Chaonians, and the Molossians were the three principal clusters of Greek tribes that had emerged from Epirus and were the most powerful among all other tribes.<ref name=\"Pyrrhus\"/>\n\nThe Molossians were also renowned for their vicious hounds, which were used by shepherds to guard their flocks. This is where the canine breed [[Molossus (dog)|Molossoid]], native to Greece, received its name. [[Virgil]] tells us that in  [[ancient Greece]] the heavier Molossian dogs were often used by the [[Greeks]] and [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] for hunting (''canis venaticus'') and to watch over the house and livestock (''canis pastoralis''). \"Never, with them on guard,\" says Virgil, \"need you fear for your stalls a midnight thief, or onslaught of wolves, or [[Iberians|Iberian]] brigands at your back.\"\n\n[[Strabo]] records that the Thesprotians, Molossians and [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonians]] referred to old men as ''pelioi'' (\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf\u03af) and old women as ''peliai'' (\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1\u03af) (<[[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] ''*pel-'', \"grey\"). Cf. [[Ancient Greek]] \u03c0\u03ad\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 ''peleia'', \"[[pigeon]]\", so-called because of its dusky [[grey]] color. Ancient Greek \u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03cc\u03c2 ''pelos'' meant \"grey\".<ref>{{harvnb|Liddell|Scott|1889}}: [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0058%3Aentry%3D%2325405 \u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03cc\u03c2].</ref> Their senators were called ''Peligones'' (\u03a0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03b3\u03cc\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2), similar to Macedonian ''[[Peliganes]]'' (\u03a0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03b3\u1fb6\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2).<ref>{{harvnb|Liddell|Scott|1889}}: [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dpeliga%3Dnes \u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b9\u03b3\u1fb6\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2].</ref>\n\n==Molossian royalty==\nThe most famed member of the Molossian dynasty was [[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]], who became famous for his [[Pyrrhic victory]] over the [[Roman Republic|Romans]]. According to [[Plutarch]], [[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]] was the son of [[Aeacides of Epirus]] and a [[Greeks|Greek]] woman from [[Thessaly]] named [[Phthia of Epirus|Phthia]], the daughter of a war hero in the [[Lamian War]]. Pyrrhus was a second cousin of [[Alexander the Great]]. In the 4th century BC, they had adopted the term for office of ''prostatai'' (Greek: \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9) literally meaning \"protectors\" like most Greek tribal states at the time.<ref>{{harvnb|Horsley|1987|p=243}}; {{harvnb|Hornblower|2002|p=199}}.</ref> Other terms for office were ''grammateus'' (Greek: \u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03cd\u03c2) meaning \"secretary\", ''demiourgoi'' (Greek: \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf\u03af) literally meaning \"creators\", ''hieromnemones'' (Greek: \u1f31\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03bd\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2) literally meaning \"of the sacred memory\" and ''synarchontes'' (Greek: \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2) literally meaning \"co-rulers\".<ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1994|p=431}}.</ref> An inscription from the 4th century stated (referring to [[Alexander I of Epirus]]):<ref>{{harvnb|Brock|Hodkinson|2000|p=250}}.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|When King was Alexandros when of Molossoi prostatas was Aristomachos Omphalas secretary was Menedamos Omphalas resolved by the assembly of the Molossoi; Kreston is benefactor hence to give citizenship to Kteson and descent line}}\n\nThe shrine of [[Dodona]] was used for the display of public decisions.<ref>{{harvnb|Brock|Hodkinson|2000|p=257}}.</ref> Despite having a monarchy, the Molossians sent princes to Athens to learn of democracy, and they did not consider certain aspects of democracy incompatible with their form of government.<ref>{{harvnb|Alcock|Osborne|2007|p=392}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Brock|Hodkinson|2000|p=256}}.</ref>\n\n[[Olympias]], the mother of Alexander the Great, was a member of this celebrated sovereign house.\n\n==War==\nIn 385 BC, the [[Illyrians]], aided by [[Dionysius I of Syracuse|Dionysius]] of [[Syracuse, Italy|Syracuse]], attacked the Molossians, attempting to place the exile [[Alcetas I of Epirus|Alcetas]] on the throne.<ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1986|p=479}}.</ref> Dionysius planned to control all the Ionian Sea. [[Sparta]] intervened and expelled the Illyrians who were led by [[Bardyllis]].<ref>Diodorus Siculus. ''Library'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Diod.+15.13.1 15.13.1].</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Hammond|1986|p=470}}.</ref><ref name=Hammond428>{{harvnb|Hammond|1994|p=428}}.</ref> Even with the aid of 2,000 Greek [[hoplites]] and 500 suits of Greek armour, the [[Illyrians]] were defeated by the Spartans (led by [[Agesilaus II|Agesilaus]]) but not before ravaging the region and killing 15,000 Molossians.<ref name=Hammond428/>\n\nIn another Illyrian attack in 360 BC, the Molossian king [[Arymbas]] (or Arybbas) evacuated his non-combatant population to [[Aetolia]] and let the Illyrians loot freely. The stratagem worked, and the Molossians fell upon the Illyrians, who were encumbered with booty, and defeated them.<ref name=Hammond428/><ref>Diodorus Siculus. ''Library'', 14.92, 15.2, 16.2.</ref>\n\n==List of Molossians==\n\n*[[Pyrrhus of Epirus]] (318\u2013272 BC) most prominent Epirote king.\n*[[Neoptolemus]] son of [[Achilles]] and [[Deidamia (mythology)|Deidamia]] ([[List of Ancient Epirotes#Aeacid dynasty|Aeacid dynasty]] till 231 BC).\n*[[Molossus (son of Neoptolemus)|Molossus]] son of Neoptolemus and [[Andromache]].\n*Alcon (6th century BC) suitor of [[Agariste of Sicyon]].\n*[[Admetus of Epirus|Admetus]], who gave asylum to [[Themistocles]].\n*Eidymmas prostates, secretary Amphikorios gave citizenship \u03c4\u03bf Philista, wife of Antimachos from Arrhonos, under King [[Neoptolemus I of Epirus|Neoptolemos I]] 370\u2013368 BC.<ref>Cabanes, L'\u00c9pire 534,1.</ref>\n*Tharyps [[theorodokos]] in [[Epidauros]] 365 BC.<ref>IG IV\u00b2,1 95 Line 31.</ref>\n*Myrtale [[Olympias]] mother of [[Alexander the Great]] circa 376\u2013316 BC.\n*Arybbas winner in [[Tethrippon]] [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympics]] 344 BC.<ref>{{harvnb|Woodbury|1979|pp=95\u2013133}}.</ref>\n*Aristomachos prostates, secretary Menedamos gave citizenship to Simias of [[Apollonia, Illyria|Apollonia]], resident at Theptinon, under King [[Alexander I of Epirus|Alexander I]] 342\u2013330/329 BC.<ref>Cabanes, L'\u00c9pire 540,4.</ref>\n*[[Deidamia II of Epirus]] (died circa 233 BC) last surviving representative of the royal Aeacid dynasty.\n*Kephalos, Antinoos sided with Perseus against the Romans ([[Third Macedonian War]]) circa 170 BC.<ref>{{harvnb|Smith|1844|p=191}}: \"ANTI'NOUS (\u0386\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2), a chief among the Molossians in Epeirus, who became involved, against his own will, in the war of Perseus, king of Macedonia, against the Romans.\"</ref>\n\n==Family tree of kings of Epirus==\n{{familytree/start}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | Aea |Aea=[[Aeacidae|AEACIDAE]]}}\n{{familytree| | }}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | Tha |Tha=[[Tharrhypas]]<br>king of Epirus<br>430-392 BC}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | }}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | Al1 |Al1=[[Alcetas I of Epirus|Alcetas I]]<br>king of Epirus<br>390-370 BC}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|(| }}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | Ne1 | | | | | | | | |F|~|~|~|~| Ary |Ne1=[[Neoptolemus I of Epirus|Neoptolemus I]]<br>king of Epirus<br>370-357 BC|Ary=[[Arybbas of Epirus|Arybbas]]<br>king of Epirus<br>370-343 BC}}\n{{familytree| | | | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| | | | | |:| |,|-|-|-|(| }}\n{{familytree| Ph2 |y| Oly |F| Al1 | | Tro |~|~|~|~|J| Ac2 | | Aea |~| Phh |Al1=[[Alexander I of Epirus|Alexander I]]<br>king of Epirus<br>343/2-331 BC|Oly=[[Olympias]]|Ac2=[[Alcetas II of Epirus|Alcetas II]]<br>king of Epirus<br>313-306 BC|Aea=[[Aeacides of Epirus|Aeacides]]<br>king of Epirus<br>331-316, 313 BC|Phh=[[Phthia of Epirus|Phthia]]<br><small>daughter of<br>[[Menon IV of Pharsalus]]|Tro=Troas|Ph2=[[Philip II of Macedon|Philip II]]<br>king of Macedon}}\n{{familytree| |,|-|^|-|.| |:| |!| | | |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|(| }}\n{{familytree| Al3 | |Cle|J| Ne2 | | Dei |~| De1 |~| Lan |~| Py1 |~| Ant |Ne2=[[Neoptolemus II of Epirus|Neoptolemus II]]<br>king of Epirus<br>302-297 BC|Py1=[[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus I]]<br>king of Epirus 306-302 BC,<br>of Macedon 274-272 BC,<br>of Syracusse 278-276 BC<br><small>\u221e 3.[[Bircenna]]|Ant=1.[[Antigone of Epirus|Antigone]]<br><small>daughter of<br>[[Philip (husband of Berenice I of Egypt)|Philip]] and [[Berenice I of Egypt|Berenice I]]|Lan=2.[[Lanassa (wife of Pyrrhus)|Lanassa]]<br><small>daughter of<br>[[Agathocles of Syracuse]]<br>king of Sicily|Dei=[[Deidamia I of Epirus|Deidamia I]]|De1=[[Demetrius I of Macedon|Demetrius I Poliorketes]]<br>king of Macedon<Br><small>\u221e [[Phila (daughter of Antipater)|Phila]]|Al3=[[Alexander the Great]]<br>king of Macedon<br>lord of Asia|Cle=[[Cleopatra of Macedon|Cleopatra]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | An2 | | Pto | | Al2 |~| Ol2 |Ol2=(1) [[Olympias II of Epirus|Olympias II]]<br>|Pto=(1) [[Ptolemy (son of Pyrrhus)|Ptolemy]]<br>military officer|Al2=(2) [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander II]]<br>king of Epirus<br>272-242 BC|An2=[[Antigonos II Gonatas]]<br>king of Macedon}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| }}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | De2 |~| Pht | | Py2 | | Ptm |Py2=[[Pyrrhus II of Epirus|Pyrrhus II]]<Br>king of Epirus<br>242-238 BC|Ptm=[[Ptolemy of Epirus|Ptolemy]]<br>king of Epirus<br>238-235 BC|Pht=[[Phthia of Macedon|Phthia]]|De2=[[Demetrius II of Macedon|Demetrius II]]<br>king of Macedon}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |,|-|-|-|(| | | |!| }}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | Ner | | De2 | | Py3 |Ner=[[Nereis of Epirus|Nereis]]<br><small>\u221e [[Gelo, son of Hiero II|Gelo]]<br>king of Syracuse|De2=[[Deidamia II of Epirus|Deidamia II]]<br>queen of Epirus<br>235-c.231 BC|Py3=[[Pyrrhus III of Epirus|Pyrrhus III]]<br>king of Epirus<br>235 BC}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chaonia]]\n*[[Chaonians]]\n*[[Olympias]]\n*[[Orestis (region)]]\n*[[Pyrrhus of Epirus]]\n*[[Thesprotians]]\n*[[Invasion of Molossia]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Alcock|first1=Susan E.|last2=Osborne|first2=Robin|title=Classical Archaeology|location